@node "Main" "Control Panel V6 Prefs"
@{fg shine}@{b}Control Panel 6 Preferences Editor@{ub}@{fg text}

This preference program allows you to edit the preferences of the main
program CP6 and the included dialler Amiconnect.
Prior to this release these 2 programs were completely separate and had
separate preference interfaces, with this release the programs have been
more integral although still retaining some individuality.

@{b}Control Panel@{ub}

@{"Main Prefs" link "mainprefs"} Main Control Panel Prefs
@{"Display   " link "display"} Screen & Display Options
@{"Programs  " link "program"} Assign Programs to Buttons
@{"Options   " link "option"} Setup Options Menu
@{"Edit      " link "edit"} Setup Edit Menu

@{b}Amiconnect@{ub}

@{"User Details    " link "user"} Edit User Information
@{"Modem Details   " link "modem"} Edit Modem Configuration
@{"Network Driver  " link "network"} Edit Sana2/Network Driver Configuration
@{"Provider Details" link "pop"} Edit Internet Service Provider Details
@{"Logon Details   " link "logon"} Edit Logon Details
@{"Save Prefs As   " link "saveas"} Save Preferences File
@{"Load Prefs File " link "loadac"} Load Preferences File

This Amigauide file may be automatically accessed by switching on the option
at the bottom of the initial prefs requester, this will only work with
Amigaguide and will not work with Multiview.

This is part of the Control Panel 6 package, if you require any help in
configuring your setup or have any comments or reports of bugs please e-mail
Martin hunt at cp6@mchunt.demon.co.uk.

Control Panel 6 is Shareware Please Register
@endnode
@node "user" "Amiconnect User Preferences"
@{fg shine}User Prefs@{fg text}

@{b}E-Mail Address@{ub}
Enter your e-mail address here
@{b}Real Name@{ub}
Enter your full name
@{b}Organisation@{ub}
If you are a business user enter your business name here otherwise enter
anything you like such as your web page address.
@{b}Home Directory@{ub}
Enter the path of your home directory, this directory is usually used for
little bits and pieces and sometimes config files.
@{b}Mail System@{ub}
When amiconnect has connected and the connection has been confirmed several
programs will be started to collect and send news and mail. Amiconnect
allows 4 options of how this takes place these being

. Normal SMTP Mail and NNTP News
  starts mailkick and nntptransfer, you need a smtp daemon setup
  to   collect mail.
. Airmail Mail and NNTP News
  tells Airmail to collect and send mail and starts nntptransfer
. Thor News and SMTP Mail
  Gets mail and news using Thor's sendtcp and gettcp commands
. Thor News and POP Mail
  as above but if your mail is collected from a POP mailserver

@{b}Collect News@{ub}
If selected Amiconnect will collect news if it isn't selected Amiconnect
will not collect news.

@{b}Enable Speech@{ub}
Providing that you have the say command installed and the associated
libraries Amiconnect will speak error and info messages to you.

@{b}Enable Sound@{ub}
Providing that you have installed DSound (available from mus/play on aminet) 
in your c: or amitcp:bin directory, Amiconnect will play samples to indicate
certain events. The sound samples are stored in cp:

ERROR messages will play cp:error.iff
When you connect to your provider cp:connect.iff will play
Once login hasn't taken place and a good connection has been verified 
cp:established.iff will play.
When you disconnect cp:disconnect.iff will play

A set of samples is included, but you may choose your own.

@{B}SAVE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env: and Envarc:
@{B}USE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env:
@{b}CANCEL@{UB}
Do not save changes

@{b}
@endnode
@node "modem" "Amiconnect Modem Preferences"
@{fg shine}Modem Prefs@{fg text}

This part of Amiconnect is probably the most difficult to setup and the most
vital, if the details here are incorrect you will not be able to logon.
Please have your modem manual handy as you will need it, all defaults are
for a USR 14400 Sportster Modem.

@{b}Serial Device@{ub}
This should be set to the serial device you are using, serial.device is the
standard device supplied with your Amiga but an alternative device such as
artser.device will usually give better results.
@{b}Device Number@{ub}
The device number of your serial port, necessary if you have more than one
port.
@{b}Baud Rate@{ub}
The baud rate of the transfer, this should be set above the speed of your
modem as this will allow your modems compression routines to be utilised,
unless you have special fast serial ports you should not set this above
57600. 38400 is recommended for 14K4 modems and 57600 for 28K8 modems.
@{b}Sana2/TCPIP Dev.@{ub}
This is to specify what sort of dial up connection you have, nowadays most
providers use PPP but if you can use CSLIP this may be faster. Dynamic SLIP
connections are not supported but dynamic PPP connections are.
@{b}Init. Modem@{ub}
Enter your modems initialisation string here, this will usually be ATZ.
@{b}Dial Command@{ub}
Enter the command used to dial out, do not include the phone number here
just the AT command ATDT for tone compatable exchanges and ATDP for pulse
dial exchanges.
@{b}DTR Overide On@{ub}
Enter the command here that turns the modems Data Terminal Ready overide on,
you may also need to alter a dip switch. On a USR 14K4 Sportster switch 1
should be down.
@{b}DTR Overide Off@{ub}
Enter the command to reverse the prvious and turn the Data Terminal Ready
overide off.
@{b}Modem Hang Up@{ub}
Enter the command needed to take your modem offhook should be ATH.
@{b}Command Mode@{ub}
Enter the command your modem needs to start accepting new AT commands during
a transmission
@{b}Set Data Rate@{ub}
Enter the command used to tell the modem to communicate with the computer at
the current baud rate, this is often referred to as the DTE rate (Data Terminal Exchange rate).
If not known try entering just At and see if you can connect.
@{b}OK Message@{ub}
The response your modem gives when a command has been successfully completed

@{B}SAVE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env: and Envarc:
@{B}USE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env:
@{b}CANCEL@{UB}
Do not save changes

@endnode
@node "network" "Amiconnect Network Driver Preferences"
@{fg shine}Network Driver Prefs@{fg text}

These options are additional parameters for the env:sana2/###.config files
that control the network driver. By adjusting them you can achieve maximum
throughput from your connection.

Please note that for unregistered version of the PPP driver you should leave
the last 2 options off, as PPP will fail otherwise.

@{b}7Wire@{ub}
This selects hardware handshaking (CTS/RTS) it is highly recommended if you
are using high baud rates. You must have a good fully connected serial cable
to use this option, but you should have one of these anyway.

@{b}CD@{ub}
This makes the computers take notice of the carrier detect line.
This line tells your software and your hosts software when data transmission
is possible.

@{b}EOFMODE@{ub}
This reduces the load on the CPU quite considerably but will not work with
all serial devices, try it and if it doesn't work switch it off.

@{b}MTU Enable@{ub}
This enables the setting of the Maximum Transfer Unit, if this gadget is
activated the value below will be used as the MTU value otherwise the
default value will be taken.

@{b}MTU@{ub}
This sets the Maximum Transfer Unit, this value should be the same as that
used by the provider you are using, most use 1006 which is the default for
slip and cslip. This figure should be inbetween 576 and 1500 and should be
even.

@{B}SAVE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env: and Envarc:
@{B}USE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env:
@{b}CANCEL@{UB}
Do not save changes

@endnode
@node "pop" "Amiconnect Service Provider Preferences"
@{fg shine}Provider Prefs@{fg text}

These details all refer to your internet service provider and your own
account details, if you are unsure of any of the setting emailing your
provider may be a good idea. Good service providers will provide all this
information when you open your account.

@{b}Your IP No.@{ub}
Enter your Internet Protocol number if you are using a PPP connection you
may enter 0.0.0.0 to allow automatic IP number setting.
@{b}Gateways IP No.@{ub}
Enter the Internet Protocol number of the computer you are connecting to.
@{b}Mail Server@{ub}
The address of the server where your mail is stored, usually has some
reference to post or mail followed by your providers name.
@{b}News Server@{ub}
The server you collect your usenet news rom, most large service providers
have their own newsservers but if you are using a small provider you may
have to find a suitable newsfeed.
@{b}HTTP/FTP/GOPHER/WAIS Proxy@{ub}
This is the address if a machine that buffers/cache's WWW pages to provide
faster access and sometimes to improve site security. You may leave these
options blank if your provider hasn't got a proxy server, the defaults will
work but may be slow.
@{b}POP1 Name@{ub}
Enter a name for your main connection point, this will appear in the
connection logfiles
@{b}POP1 Phone No.@{ub}
Enter the phone number of the above connection point, you may need to
include special charactes such as 'W' if you are dialling from an extension.
i.e. 0645123666 would become 9W0645123666 from an extension.
@{b}POP2/Phone2@{ub}
As the above but for your backup/secondary connection point.

@{B}SAVE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env: and Envarc:
@{B}USE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env:
@{b}CANCEL@{UB}
Do not save changes

@endnode
@node "logon" "Amiconnect Logon Preferences"
@{fg shine}Logon Prefs@{fg text}
This requester is used to setup the details you need to send to your
providers computer inorder to logon. If your provider has a logon procedure
similar to that which follows Amiconnect will handle it internally, if
not you will need to create a custom logonscript using the supplied utility
or manually using an editor. The supplied utility will save the file as
amitcp:db/aclogon.script, but you may move or rename this.

@{b}Standard Login Procedure@{ub}
(ISP) Login:
(YOU) username
(ISP) Password
(YOU) your password
(ISP) Protocol
(YOU) PPP or SLIP

@{b}Login Prompt@{ub}
The prompt which is displayed to ask you your user name usually @{fg shine}login:@{fg text} but
sometimes @{fg shine}username:@{fg text}
@{b}Response@{ub}
Your response to the Login Prompt
@{b}Protocol Prompt@{ub}
The prompt which appears to ask you whether you are using SLIP or PPP
usually @{fg shine}Protocol:@{fg text}.
@{b}Password Prompt@{ub}
Prompt asking you to enter your password for that account usually @{fg shine} Password:@{fg text}
@{b}Password{ub}
Your response to the password prompt, i.e. your password
@{b}Custom Script@{ub}
If your providers login procedure is not like the standard login procedure
you will need to write a custom script, in this box you should enter the
filename of this script including the full path. The supplied Create
Advanced Login script will make a file called amitcp:db/aclogon.script.

@{b}
@{B}SAVE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env: and Envarc:
@{B}USE@{ub}
Saves current settings to Env:
@{b}CANCEL@{UB}
Do not save changes

@endnode
@node "saveas" "Amiconnect Save Prefs File"
@{fg shine}Save Prefs@{fg text}
Saves all the current settings as a specified file, which can be loaded by
the load prefs file option. This option allows you to have more than one
amiconnect setup, and therefore use more than one service provider.
I currently have one setup for Zynet and one for Demon.
@endnode
@node "loadac" "Amiconnect Load Prefs File"
@{fg shine}Load Prefs@{fg text}
Loads the prefs file saved by the Save Prefs As option, the settings in the
file become the current settings in Env: and are therefore get removed when
you reboot. To make these settings permanent go into one of the amiconnect
prefs editors and select save, this will transfer all the Env:AC! variables
to envarc: and make them the default settings.
@endnode
@node "mainprefs" "Control Panel Main Preferences"
@{fg shine}Main Preferences@{fg text}

@{b}CP Directory@{ub}            Enter the directory where Control Panel is installed
@{b}AmiTCP Directory@{ub}        Enter the directory Where AmiTCP is installed

For the following four options you should enter amitcp:bin/amiconnect in the first box
if you are using the Amiconnect dialler which is provided. The parameters for amiconnect
are shown in brackets.

@{b}Start AmiTCP Cmd.@{ub}       Command and parameters to start amitcp            (start)
@{b}Stop AmiTCP Cmd.@{ub}        Command and parameters to stop amitcp             (stop)
@{b}Connect Cmd.@{ub}            Command and parameters to connect to the net      (up)
@{b}Disconnect Cmd.@{ub}         Command and parameters to disconnect from the net (down)

@{b}Save Logfile@{ub} Do you want to save a logfile for use with Phonebill?
@{b}Logfile@{ub} What do you want this logfile to be called.

@{b}Start AmiTCP On Startup@{ub} Do you want AmiTCP to start running when CP is initially run?
@{b}Status@{ub} What level of status information do you want, No Information is recommended.

@{b}SAVE@{ub} Save Settings and Exits Editor
@{b}CANCEL@{ub} Exits Editor
@endnode
@node "display" "Control Panel Screen & Display Preferences"
@{fg shine}Display Prefs@{fg text}
This requester allows you to alter how Control Panel will be displayed.

@{B}Public Screen Name@{ub}
The name of the public screen that Control Panel will appear on, if you want
Control Panel to appear on the workbench you should set this to Workbench.
Please note that this option is case sensitive and workbench or WORKBENCH
will cause Control Panel to not open properly.
@{b}Backdrop@{ub}
If selected Control Panel will appear as a backdrop on the chosen screen and
no window will be opened.
@{b}Default Display@{ub}
This selects what mode Control Panel will start up in, this mode may be
changed later by pressing the mode key on the main Control Panel.
@{b}Save Position@{ub}
If selected the position of Control Panel on the screen will be saved when
you exit the program or change modes.
@{b}Normal/Horizontal/Vertical Display@{ub}
These options control the starting position of Control Panel in each of the
available modes, the left offset settings are pixels from the left of the
screen and the top offset is pixes from the top. If the values given are out
of range Control Panel will start in a default position.

@{b}SAVE@{ub} Save Settings and Exits Editor
@{b}CANCEL@{ub} Exits Editor
@endnode

@node "program" "Control Panel Program Assignment"
@{fg shine}Program Prefs@{fg text}

This editor controls what programs the main buttons on the Control Panel
load and run. The text in brackets is that which is on the buttons followed
by an expansion.

To change the settings click on the name of the button you want to edit and
then enter the program name into the box by the text @{b}Program:@{ub} yiou
may use the file selector which can be activated by pressing the @{b}F@{ub}
button to select this program.
Then fill out the @{b}Parameters@{ub} box with any necessary parameters,
finally change the stack setting to an appropriate value 4096 will be
adequate for most programs but Amosaic and Grapevine will require higher
values to work succesfully.

When you have edited all the buttons you need to press the @{b}SAVE@{ub}
button to save the changes or @{b}CANCEL@{ub} to forget the changes.
@endnode

@node "option" "Control Panel Options Setup"
@{fg shine}Option Prefs@{fg text}

Control Panel allows 3 options which appear as buttons and menus and then a
lot more menu options (memory & space permitting). This editor will allow
you to setup these options.

@{B}Adding A New Option@{ub}

Press the @{b}Add Item@{ub} Button
Enter the name you wish to appear on the menu bar (and button for the first
3 options) into the @{b}Menu Text:@{ub} box.
Then enter the program filename into the @{b}Program:@{ub} box or use the
file selector @{b}F@{ub}.
When you have done this enter any parameters that program needs into the
@{b}Parameters:@{ub} box.
Finally adjust the Stack to a suitable value by entering a value in the
@{b}Stack:@{ub} box.

@{b}Changing an Option@{ub}

Click on the item you wish to change and then alter the necessary boxes, see
above for more details on what each box does.

When finished editing press the @{b}SAVE@{ub} button to save the changes
or @{b}CANCEL@{ub} to forget the changes.

@endnode

@node "edit" "Control Panel Edit Setup"
@{fg shine}Edit Prefs@{fg text}

The editor menu allows the editing of files by just selecting the item on the
menu, ideal for editing regularly edited files such as your user-startup.

@{B}Adding A New Edit Option@{ub}

Press the @{b}Add Item@{ub} Button
Enter the name you wish to appear on the menu bar3 into the @{b}Menu Text:@{ub} box.
Then enter the filename into the @{b}Program:@{ub} box or use the
file selector @{b}F@{ub}.

@{b}Changing an Option@{ub}

Click on the item you wish to change and then alter the necessary boxes.

When finished editing press the @{b}SAVE@{ub} button to save the changes
or @{b}CANCEL@{ub} to forget the changes.

@endnode



